    <h1>    Welcome to the World of CrossFit</h1>
    <h2>    What is CrossFit?</h2>
    <p> CrossFit is a high-intensity fitness program incorporating elements from several sports and types of exercise. Instead of isolating muscles, it focuses on functional movements—actions you perform in your daily life, like squatting, pulling, and pushing. The ultimate goal is to improve your overall physical preparedness, build strength, and increase endurance.</p>
    <h2>    How is it Different from a Regular Gym?</h2>
    <p> If you walk into a CrossFit "Box" (that's what they call the gym), you won't see rows of treadmills or weight machines. Instead, you'll find barbells, kettlebells, pull-up bars, and plenty of open space.
The biggest difference, however, is the community. You don't plug in your earphones and work out alone. You train together in group classes led by a coach, cheering each other on. This team spirit makes pushing through tough workouts much easier and a lot more fun!</p>
    <h2>    The CrossFit Dictionary</h2>
    <h3>Every day is different in CrossFit. To survive your first class, here are some essential terms you need to know:</h3>
    <ul>    
            <li>  <h4>WOD (Workout of the Day):</h4> <p>    This is the core of the daily class. It changes every single day to keep your body guessing and adapting.</p> </li>
           <hr />   
        <li> <h4>  EMOM (Every Minute on the Minute): </h4> <p> A type of workout where you start an exercise at the top of a minute, finish the required reps, and use whatever time is left in that minute to rest before the next minute begins.  </p>   </li>
             <hr /> 
        <li> <h4>  AMRAP (As Many Rounds/Reps As Possible): </h4>  <p> A challenge to complete a specific circuit of exercises as many times as you can within a set time limit. </p> </li>
    </ul>
